alessandro.farace 22-Jul-20 04:46 AM
We now apply an additional reflection ( Us ) about the state |sâŸ© : Us=2|sâŸ©âŸ¨s|âˆ’1 . This is step 3 in the grover protocol. Can someone explain why does this lead to a reflection about |sâŸ© ?
@Anonymous K. because if you apply Us to |s> you get Us |s> = |s> (so the state remains the same) but if you apply Us to any other state (orthogonal to |s>) you get Us|orth> = 2|s><s|orth> - |orth> = -|orth> (so the state changes sign). Every state orthogonal to |s> changes sign, then you can call this a reflection about |s>.

alessandro.farace 22-Jul-20 05:31 AM
@Anonymous Uf|s> is a superposition of |s> and - 2sin(theta/2) |w> . how is this orthogonal to |s> ?
@Anonymous K. if you check the qiskit page, you can find this Î¸=arcsinâŸ¨s|wâŸ©=arcsin1/sqrt(N), which means that |w> is not equal to |s> (if they are equal, then Î¸=0). If it's not equal to |s>, then it must have some component orthogonal to |s>. In other words you can write |w> = a |s> + b |s_orthogonal> (where a and b are some coefficients that can be computed). In this case it's a bit difficult to follow because you have to express the same states in different basis: one basis is the standard base made by states like |00....0>, |00....1>, ...; another base includes |s> as a vector; another base includes |w> as a vector. I would suggest to read something about change of basis if you are unfamiliar with this

@Anonymous how to do this
Vincent 22-Jul-20 05:11 PM
Type a `, then type some stuff, then type another `
e.g. this:
hello `world`
becomes this:
hello world
For more formatting tips, see https://discordapp.com/channels/729706617951485954/734521959374913597/735283909260214272 (edited)

pmishra 22-Jul-20 06:49 PM
Finally done
2
Vincent 22-Jul-20 06:49 PM
@Anonymous Borja You can construct an n-bit QFT gate using QFT(n). If you want an approximate version, you can add approximation_degree=n as an argument. If you want the inverse QFT, you can add inverse=True as an argument. You can add this gate to the circuit using circuit.append. For instance, if you want to apply a QFT to qubits 0 through 3, you can use
mycircuit.append(QFT(4), [0, 1, 2, 3])
Carla Borja 22-Jul-20 06:50 PM
Thanks @Anonymous !
Vincent 22-Jul-20 06:52 PM
@Anonymous Yes, that construction should work in the general case. As Harold Co said, for a controlled operation on a single qubit, there are built-in operators.

@Anonymous Yep, the QASM output will be different

Codie(R.P) 23-Jul-20 02:03 PM
I think in the noiseless simulator this won't make a difference, but on a physical device it might. I'm not super familiar with the details though

Henry Liu 23-Jul-20 02:13 PM
I think the barrier is primarily related to the ordering of measurements. You're right that the barrier is not an actual operation, but without the barrier the measurements might not take place at the right time step. Off the top of my head this could be an issue if you're expecting measurement backaction, like in some error correction cases

Maybe you are missing the 2 in the exponent of the cu1 gate
in shor's algorithm section of the qiskit textbook, in the dft_dagger function, the cu1 gate is implemented as qc.cu1(-np.pi/float(2**(j-m)), m, j)
it seems that you are missing the 2**

rnva 23-Jul-20 08:32 PM
I tried following the discussion just above but I don't fully understand why the do_swaps should be set to False if using the IBM QFT. My code is here and it works but I didn't understand why I had to change the swaps. def initialize_qubits(given_circuit, n, m): given_circuit.h(range(n)) given_circuit.x(n+m-1) def modular_exponentiation(given_circuit, n, m, a): for i in range(n): qargs = list(range(n, n+m)) qargs = [i] + qargs c_U = a_x_mod15(a, 2**i) given_circuit.append(c_U, qargs) def apply_iqft(given_circuit, measurement_qubits): gate = QFT(num_qubits=len(measurement_qubits), approximation_degree=0, do_swaps=False, inverse=True, insert_barriers=False, name='iqft') given_circuit.append(gate, measurement_qubits)
mbacvanski 23-Jul-20 08:46 PM
I think the reason do_swaps should be false is because in the classical post-processing of the outputs, every time the array measured_value is read, its order is first reversed using measured_value[::-1]. Because this reversal is happening classically, there is no need for the built-in reversal of order using swaps in the default QFT. (edited)

The arguement I had at uni goes something like this: call the measurement outcome c which is promised to be in the form jN/x we can rearrange this to c/N=j/x , now the left handside is completely known and the right hand side is completely unknown if j and x are co prime we can simply the lhs and read off j and x. This happens with probability loglogN or something that appeared in the original complexity of shors algorithm!
so in this case they arent co prime and we cant find x and get a good factorization

tiago939 24-Jul-20 09:09 PM
@Anonymous R qft (and iqft) gives you the reverse order of qubits, so you need to invert them (swap) so you can have the correct order when you do the measurements
@Anonymous Bernier you have to find a line that connects the 19 qubits, respecting the connections build in the physical system (the fakeTokyo in this case), imagine each number as a city and the connections as roads, find a path that lets you visit each city only once
Jean Bernier 24-Jul-20 09:15 PM
@Anonymous thanks, I´m trying but always I need to repeat if I want to respect the physical system
tiago939 24-Jul-20 09:19 PM
@Anonymous Bernier you cannot repeat, there are some paths that connect each qubit only once, imagine these paths as one dimensional line, each qubit has a unique position on this line, the puzzle here is to find one these paths

Hint for Lab-5: Think the FakeTokyo qubits interconnection as a graph. All you need is find the Hamiltonian path of the graph. A Hamiltonian path is a path in an undirected or directed graph that visits each vertex exactly once.

AndrewE 27-Jul-20 07:19 PM
Hi! Could anyone clarify why the qubit behaves like an electric dipole and in particular, why it is represented as a linear combination of \sigma^+ and \sigma^-? I couldn't quite follow how this came about? I thought the qubit would just be a 2x1 vector.
@Anonymous Transmon qubits are designed, in part, to behave like an antenna so that they can interact with applied electric fields for control and measurement operations. Conventionally there are two metal pads separated by some distance and connected by an inductance; the metal pads have some capacitance, so charge can build up on each. This build-up of charge separated by some distance is roughly the definition of an electric dipole. Classically, one would expect an applied field oscillating in sync with the resonance of the capacitance and inductance to drive a large, oscillating separation of charge on the two metal pads. A different choice of capacitor geometry could be used to suppress the dipole moment (e.g. https://arxiv.org/pdf/1509.08014.pdf). Sorry I haven't checked the source material for comparison so may be slightly off, but usually the sigma^+ and sigma^- operators describe the dipole interaction between the qubit and electric field. Each term may be interpreted as a physical process that acts on the state (i.e. it is a matrix that acts on your 2x1 vector, or a larger vector if you also include the state of the electric field). For the dipole interaction, the important interaction terms are typically (sigma^+)(a) in which the qubit gains energy while the EM-field loses energy, and the reverse process (sigma^-)(a^+). (disclaimer: +/- might be backwards on the sigmas above) (edited)

Submit a question for the Careers in Quantum panelists using !careerquestions (Your Question!) - make sure and submit them by Wednesday, July 29, so the panelists will be able to see them all! Will the lectures and labs be recorded?  Yes! You can join live, or watch the content on-demand. Links will be posted daily in Discord - just use the command !link to see them all. ppajarillo 30-Jul-20 02:32 AM
Lab 8 PySCF Issue Installing PySCF works on almost all Linux systems, and most of Mac OS X systems, and the Ubuntu subsystems on Windows 10. However if you're on a Windows enviroment, PySCF is not compatible. For those running into these issues you can run Lab 8 notebook on IBMQ or Colab: Using IBM Quantum Experience Step 1. Log into https://quantum-computing.ibm.com/ Step 2. Hover over the left toolbar, and click on Qiskit Notebooks Step 3. Click Import Step 4. Choose ex1.ipynb (in lab 8 folder) Step 5. Your notebook should be all set to run Using Google Colab Step 0. (For those who are first time users of Google Colab), Go to https://colab.research.google.com/ and sign in using your Gmail account. And you are ready to use Google Colab Step 1. Upload ex1.ipynb to google drive Step 2. Click on file ex1.ipynb Step 3. Click "Open With" and select Google Colab. You should now see your notebook Step 4. You'll need to install qiskit, so include the following line of code:
!pip install qiskit
Step 5. And you're all set to run (edited)
5

Lab 8 PySCF Issue Installing PySCF works on almost all Linux systems, and most of Mac OS X systems, and the Ubuntu subsystems on Windows 10. However if you're on a Windows enviroment, PySCF is not compatible. For those running into these issues you can run Lab 8 notebook on IBMQ or Colab:
>
Using IBM Quantum Experience Step 1. Log into https://quantum-computing.ibm.com/ Step 2. Hover over the left toolbar, and click on Qiskit Notebooks Step 3. Click Import Step 4. Choose ex1.ipynb (in lab 8 folder) Step 5. Your notebook should be all set to run
>
Using Google Colab Step 0. (For those who are first time users of Google Colab), Go to https://colab.research.google.com/ and sign in using your Gmail account. And you are ready to use Google Colab Step 1. Upload ex1.ipynb to google drive Step 2. Click on file ex1.ipynb Step 3. Click "Open With" and select Google Colab. You should now see your notebook Step 4. You'll need to install qiskit, so include the following line of code:
!pip install qiskit
Step 5. And you're all set to run

ppajarillo 31-Jul-20 03:42 AM
How to Run Labs from Google Colab Step 1. Unzip Lab Folder Step 2. Open up lab folder, and you'll see ex1.ipynb, a grading_tools folder and a resources folder. Step 3. Zip up grading_tools and zip up resources folders. You should now have a grading_tools.zip and resources.zip in your directory. Step 4. Upload ex1.ipynb to your Google Drive Step 5. Click on ex1.ipynb on your Google Drive and click "Open With" and select Google Colab. You should now see your lab notebook Step 6. Go to the left toolbar and select the Folder icon. The notebook is still setting up a runtime, so wait a few seconds until you are connected and see a folder called sample_data. This means you are now connected to a runtime. Step 7. Drag the two zip files you created from your computer into the file area. You should see grading_tools.zip and resources.zip loaded into your Colab directory Step 8. Before you run any code, we need to unzip those two folders. Add a code block and add the following lines
!unzip grading_tools.zip !unzip resources.zip
Step 9. Run that block of code, and that will unzip those two folders in your Google Colab notebook. You are now ready to start working on the lab :) ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ If some labs require you to load in your IBMQ account, before the
IBMQ.load_account()
type in
IBMQ.save_account('YOURAPITOKENHERE', overwrite=True)
and replace YOURAPITOKENHERE with your API token Note that when the runtime expires or whenever you reload the notebook, you will need to upload those two zip files again and run the code that unzips those two folders (edited)

ppajarillo 31-Jul-20 03:43 PM
this is my lab9-ex1 cercuit
@Anonymous You're missing a gate at the end, and the measure part
So we want to measure <X>, correct?
We actually will be doing a measurement of <X> but in the Z basis, which is the basis we do our measurement in (edited)
We know that X = HZH
^you can prove that
What we had originally was <Z> = <psi | Z | psi>
We want <X>, and we know that X = HZH
<X> = <psi | X | psi > = <psi | HZH | psi>
This can also be written as
<psi H | Z | H psi>
So all you need to do is add an H to the end of both qubits
and that will give us <X>
Let me know if that makes sense @Anonymous
Y123 31-Jul-20 03:50 PM
Let me know if that makes sense @Anonymous
@Anonymous yes tnx

Frequently Asked Questions
When are exercises and lab work due? The deadline for all completed lab workbooks is August 2nd at 11:59pm EDT. No past-due notebooks will be accepted. Note: Grading can be delayed by server-overload. Be aware of potential delays and give yourself plenty of time to support time required for submission. How can I contribute to the Qiskit Global Summer School recap video? All you need is a smartphone and yourself! Send us a video of yourself and tell us about you and your experience at the summer school. See more information online here - or use the !recapvideo command. Will the lectures and labs be recorded?  Yes! You can join live, or watch the content on-demand. Links will be posted daily in Discord - just use the command !link or !lastweek to see them all, or visit #announcements where they are posted. Will Lab materials be available if I am not a Lab student? Lab is only be accessible by lab students until August 3rd. Once the summer school concludes, lab materials and exercises will be available for all students to access and use. How long will the lab/lecture content and Discord server be available? All materials will be available until 11:59 PM EDT on August 7th. After which, the Discord server and content will no longer be available - and everyone is encouraged to join the existing Qiskit community on Slack here! Don't forget to check out the Attendee Guide - it has answers to some of the questions that haven't even been thought of yet!

Here is the code I have written so far: import numpy as np i = complex(0,1) I = np.identity(2) Z = np.matrix([[0,-i],[i,0]]) X = np.matrix([[0,1],[1,0]]) II = np.tensordot(I,I) IZ = np.tensordot(I,Z) ZI = np.tensordot(Z,I) ZZ = np.tensordot(Z,Z) XX = np.tensordot(X,X) h2_hamiltonian = (-1.0523732) * II + (0.39793742) * IZ + (-0.3979374) * ZI + (-0.0112801) * ZZ + (0.18093119) * XX eValues = h2_hamiltonian.linalg.eigvals(h2_hamiltonian) Should I be using the 4-qubit model to find the exact ground state when constructing this system?
